  abstract = {{Despite the recent availability of complete genome sequences of tumors from thousands of patients, isolating disease-causing (driver) non-coding mutations from the plethora of somatic variants is notoriously challenging, and only a handful of validated examples exist. By integrating whole-genome sequencing, gene expression, chromatin accessibility, and genetic data from TCGA, we identified 301 non-coding somatic mutations that affect gene expression in cis . These mutations cluster into 36 hotspot regions with diverse molecular mechanisms of gene expression regulation. We further show that these mutations have hallmark features of noncoding drivers; namely, that they confer a positive selection on growth, functionally disrupt transcription factor binding sites, and contribute to disease progression reflected in decreased overall patient survival.}}, 
