  issn = {0021-9258}, 
  doi = {10.1074/jbc.r117.813485}, 
  pmid = {29187597}, 
  abstract = {{Initiation and regulation of transcription by RNA polymerase II (RNAPII) in eukaryotes relies upon the control elements of promoters and enhancers. Promoters and enhancers share common architectures and functions in similar ways. The prevailing view is functional promoters and enhancers can initiate bidirectional transcription. With the acceleration of recent genome-wide studies of regulated transcription, it has become clear that transcriptional enhancers in mammalian genomes are major sources of pervasive non-coding RNA transcription. In this review, we begin with the definition of promoters and enhancers as DNA regulatory elements and focus on transcriptional enhancers in mammalian genomes. We discuss functional roles of enhancer transcription and several hypothetical mechanisms in terms of enhancer-promoter communication. We also summarize the emerging roles of enhancer RNAs (eRNAs) in early elongation, such that eRNA transcript, independent from enhancer transcription, may facilitate NELF release from paused RNAPII by acting as a lure molecule. In particular, transcriptional enhancers might modulate the release of paused RNAPII via 3D chromatin looping. Emerging evidence suggests that transcriptional enhancers may play regulatory roles in promoter-proximal pausing of RNAPII, a key rate-limiting step for productive elongation.}}, 
